Solution 1. Since the terms are nonzero, we can define \( a_{n}=\left(x_{n+1}+x_{n-1}\right) / x_{n} \) for \( n \geq 1 \). It suffices to show \( a_{1}=a_{2}=\cdots \). But \( x_{n+1}^{2}-x_{n} x_{n+2}=1=x_{n}^{2}-x_{n-1} x_{n+1} \), so
\[
\begin{aligned}
x_{n+1}\left(x_{n+1}+x_{n-1}\right) & =x_{n}\left(x_{n+2}+x_{n}\right) \\
\frac{x_{n+1}+x_{n-1}}{x_{n}} & =\frac{x_{n+2}+x_{n}}{x_{n+1}} \\
a_{n} & =a_{n+1}
\end{aligned}
\]
since \( x_{n}, x_{n+1} \neq 0 \). The result follows by induction.
Solution 2. Given \( x_{0}, x_{1}, x_{2} \), let \( a=\left(x_{0}+x_{2}\right) / x_{1} \). From \( x_{1}^{2}-x_{0} x_{2}=1 \), we get \( x_{1}^{2}-a x_{1} x_{0}+x_{0}^{2}=1 \).

Now
\[
\begin{aligned}
x_{2}^{2}-x_{1}\left(a x_{2}-x_{1}\right) & =\left(a x_{1}-x_{0}\right)^{2}-x_{1}\left(a\left(a x_{1}-x_{0}\right)-x_{1}\right) \\
& =x_{1}^{2}-a x_{1} x_{0}+x_{0}^{2}=1,
\end{aligned}
\]
so \( x_{3}=a x_{2}-x_{1} \).
By essentially the same algebra (and a simple induction), \( x_{n+1}=a x_{n}-x_{n-1} \) for all \( n \geq 1 \).

Solution 3. Let \( a=\left(x_{0}+x_{2}\right) / x_{1} \). Consider a sequence defined by \( y_{n+1}-a y_{n}+ \) \( y_{n-1}=0 \) where \( y_{i}=x_{i} \) for \( i=0,1,2 \); we wish to show that \( y_{i}=x_{i} \) for all nonnegative integers \( i \).

If \( a \neq \pm 2 \), then by the theory of linear recursive sequences (discussed after the solution to 1988A5), the general solution is
\[
y_{n}=A r^{n}+B s^{n}
\]
where \( A \) and \( B \) are constants, and \( r \) and \( s \) are the roots of the characteristic equation \( t^{2}-a t+1=0 \). Then \( r s=1 \), and \( (r-s)^{2}=a^{2}-4 \) by the quadratic formula or by the identity \( (r-s)^{2}=(r+s)^{2}-4 r s \). Now
\[
\begin{aligned}
y_{n}^{2}-y_{n+1} y_{n-1} & =\left(A r^{n}+B s^{n}\right)^{2}-\left(A r^{n-1}+B s^{n-1}\right)\left(A r^{n+1}+B s^{n+1}\right) \\
& =-A B(r s)^{n-1}(r-s)^{2} \\
& =-A B\left(a^{2}-4\right)
\end{aligned}
\]
which is independent of \( n \). Thus \( y_{n}^{2}-y_{n+1} y_{n-1}=y_{1}^{2}-y_{2} y_{0}=1 \) for all \( n \), so \( y_{n}=x_{n} \) by induction on \( n \).

If \( a= \pm 2 \), then the general solution is
\[
y_{n}=(A+B n)( \pm 1)^{n}
\]

Then
\[
y_{n}^{2}-y_{n+1} y_{n-1}=B^{2}
\]
which is independent of \( n \). Hence as before, \( y_{n}^{2}-y_{n+1} y_{n-1}=y_{1}^{2}-y_{2} y_{0}=1 \) for all \( n \), so \( y_{n}=x_{n} \) for all \( n \) as well.

Solution 4. For all \( n \),
\[
\begin{aligned}
\operatorname{det}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
x_{n-1}+x_{n+1} & x_{n}+x_{n+2} \\
x_{n} & x_{n+1}
\end{array}\right) & =\operatorname{det}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
x_{n-1} & x_{n} \\
x_{n} & x_{n+1}
\end{array}\right)+\operatorname{det}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
x_{n+1} & x_{n+2} \\
x_{n} & x_{n+1}
\end{array}\right) \\
& =-1+1=0
\end{aligned}
\]

Thus \( \left(x_{n-1}+x_{n+1}, x_{n}+x_{n+2}\right)=a_{n}\left(x_{n}, x_{n+1}\right) \) for some scalar \( a_{n} \). Hence
\[
\frac{x_{n+1}+x_{n-1}}{x_{n}}=\frac{x_{n+2}+x_{n}}{x_{n+1}}
\]
for all \( n \geq 1 \), since \( x_{n}, x_{n+1} \neq 0 \), so we are done by induction.
